Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo in Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth American president of history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, medal and cheque of $1.4 million will be awarded to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will be landing in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy program.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who selected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides for an interview with the king of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet its summum in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third to be awarded the prize in the very centre of the Committee.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan during the award ceremony.
The President does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this award by being a president who leads a war in two countries at the present time.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to highlight.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate to charitable works, but he has not yet concretely decided which ones.
His program will then take him and his wife to a banquet, including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at that price at the beginning.
For example, he mentioned that he felt that he did not deserve it fully.
He has also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
Upon the announcement, he said it would be an "invitation to act" for him.
