Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes the lead in the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the current variants of the virus as well as on some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at the present time.
However, the lives of the sick can be dramatically extended through a mix of drugs that prevent the spread of HIV in the body.
However, their consumption results in a number of side effects.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have effect.
The work of the experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assembly of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "enhanced" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their links on the proteins of the virus.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiwalled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and linked by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
