He gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative at Washington, Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General on United Nations climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete picture."
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions from 50 to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to support floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
