Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Fecondity and professional career of women in Spain" carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of the working mothers have seen their careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of married life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment employed.
Those who do not have activities outside the home, work part-time or work poorly, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with a stable job, mainly in the public sector, are re-emerging into married life and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
