In addition, the type of employment exercised largely affects maternity, but less the common starting date," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who underwent elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another discontinuity also occurs among women, depending on their level of education.
