When a new car goes out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very hard work, as each of the thousand parts of the vehicle must be catalogued and the price recorded.
In addition, a "intelligent" graphic image of each model is created, on which you can click on the different parts of a passenger car.
If it is a model sold massively, work can be ready within a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, for example, they have information on Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
For vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To perform the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centers around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them is specialized in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than 100 technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests every year 90 million to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer varied products.
The most common application is repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of cashier parts or for the calculation of the venal or residual value of a car.
